segments.text: Mr.
Rudder didn't know that Dr. Byers had restricted my area of work to work on the entering students out of the registrar, out of the admissions office.
Now, when you first began counseling and testing, Wayne Hall was the vice president.
Describe working with him.
I'm very fond of Dr. Hall.
He was a man who, he had a sense of humor.
He had high standards, but he was very pragmatic.
I remember the ag students began to complain because they had to take the science advanced test, the GRE.
And Dr. Hall said, are you a scientist?
And the student said, yes.
He said, well, we'll take you.
Dr. Hall, he was a very fine person to work under because he knew what you were doing.
Now, Earl Rutter selected him as vice president, didn't he?
Yes.
Because I worked for Dr. Hall for two and a half years, and to me, they seemed different in personalities.
Yes.
And I've wondered how Mr. Rutter came, do you have any idea how Mr. Rutter came to identify Hall as the appropriate person to be the vice president?

I think President Rutter was a very pragmatic person, and if he felt an individual had the qualifications that he was seeking, he would never let a personal temperament or... Now did Dean, did Dr. Hall go from being
a department head to vice president?
No, he was dean of the graduate college.
Oh, that's right, that's right.
He went from, yeah.
And that was one of the difficulties that they had, as I understand it.
President Rudder, like he did in my case, he said, Wayne didn't handle both of those.
Well, that didn't last.
And Wayne...
It was unfortunate.
Now Dr.
Bars, Dr.
Bars is a very brilliant scientist currently.
Even if the boys did name the oceanography Bars' last great erection.
But Dr.
Bars
during most of my time under him, I had sort of an uncomfortable relationship.
It wasn't anything except you'd go to see him and his desk was clear.
It had a little memo pad in front of it.
And you would make your case.
And if he would reach over and scribble something on that sheet of paper, well, you could feel pretty good.
But if he just sat there, you finally got the message that he was saying, get out of here.
But I don't think he understood us.
Well, Graff told me one time, he said, I think if I understood you, I could agree with you.
Let me put into this machine an anecdote I remember about Byers one time.

I was chairman of the library committee then, and we were trying to consolidate into the newly expanded, the first expansion of the Cushing Library, and we were trying to bring all the branch libraries in.
And architecture agreed, business agreed,
Veterinary medicine, we agreed, should stay west of the tracks, that that was so separate.
And the other one was chemistry.
And chemistry said, no, no, no.
That, no, no, we've got to have our own.
Well, our budget was so limited, and what we were trying to do was to make our dollars go as far as we could.
And so we called a public discussion one night in the library of this matter.
And we asked the chemistry department to come and make their case and for Dr. Byers to be there since it all reported to him.

And one of the chemists, and I can't remember whether it was the department head or not, I think it was, he finally got near the end of his remarks and he said, well, we had hoped not to have to be this blunt with it.
But we chemists do not have time to waste like you other people do to spend our time

walking to the library we have too much to do for that and dr byers said meeting adjourned decision made chemistry library moved to the main library it's over yeah that dr buyers without question i i think that um
Well, we had Dr. Byers over in an effort to try to get a more cordial relationship.
And we showed him through the center and what we did.
And Dr. Holt was with me.
And when we finished, we said, we enjoyed having you over, Dr. Byers.
And he said, anyone ever choose
He won't say anything, but he holds it and turned and walked off.
And I said, no, Dr. Byers, no one's going to mention that.
And I said, I'll escort you back over to the cook.
He said, that isn't necessary.
I said, no, sir, it isn't, but it's going to be good.
And I walked back over there with him.
Well, as time went on, Dr.
Bars and I, we seemed to be better.
And he was never discourteous.
Haskell, Dr.
Bars, is a great man, scientist.
But he was supervising something that he didn't have a grasp of.
What can you say about Bill Graff and his years in between Hall and Myers?
I would say with all honesty that I think Texas A&M University made an error in judgment in bringing Dr. Graff to the campus for the work he did.
And I think Dr. Graff, it was unfortunate that he didn't recognize it.
I agree with you.
And because both sides seemed to understand.
And it was difficult on the people that, well I remember one time that
I got this study on the, you know, we made that famous co-ed study.
And the counselor said, that's what we didn't want to do.
He called me down there and just dumped it on me.
I said, okay, I've been trained to do that.
So we came back and we chose the most logical approach was through the family.
And more than that, we could go through the youngest child in the family, in the public schools, and get the questionnaire out.
We divided up the area, and we visited superintendents.
We did not have a single person turn us down.
Now, was this the study over here in East Texas?
No, that was Barton Nelson.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
And that was unfortunate.
That was a good scientific sample, in my opinion.
And Barton Nelson's a fine man.
but he was hurt by that.
Because I remember I was on the Aspirations Committee, and we used that study as one of our strong arguments for co-education, for broadening the curriculum.
But I've always worried that some opponents of those positive changes blame, burden,
for having done that study and reaching the conclusions that... Oh, I think that this happened.
Actually, Dr. Nelson certainly retained his reputation in sociology, but I think that his chances are being recognized.
Yes.
Well, Dean Graff had what I would call an obnoxious personality.
He could be, and with me, could be very abrupt.
Yes.
And there wasn't any, if I'm not mistaken, he was a native Texan, but he wasn't able to relate well to Texans.
Let's go on to more positive.
Share some Rudder stories.
Oh.
President Rudder,
I don't have many of them because I was not around him in a social situation.
But President Rutter, he could handle himself real well.
A group of us flew up with some students to West Point for a football game.
And President Rutter got up there, but he wasn't on that plane.
We were in the old cargo plane then.
But he, I got the feedback that he was very popular.
He was very popular.
He could be tough, or he knew when it was social, I guess.
But my relationship
I remember the last freshman night that President Rutter was alive.
See, we would have the freshman meet
for that night, and we'd either sing in the area around the old movie theater or what have you.
And we graduated to having air conditioning in the gymnasium, and so we had it in there.
There's more company.
In G. Roddick White?
G. Roddick White.
And I sat with Mrs. Rutter on the front row there, and he spoke to the boys, the young men, about the importance of choosing a good mate.
life expectancy.
It was very simple but direct.
And I had no idea that that was his last meeting.
But I dug out this old song that's published a lot.
warm beat the hearts of all thy sons, old A&M of Texas, none but the staunch, and goes through that.
President Rudder didn't recognize me.
And so he got word to me he wanted a copy of that.
Well, I sent him a copy.
But I have...
I know I was in some meetings.
I was made project coordinator of the Rudder Conference Center.
I didn't even know what it was.
We were flying back from Chicago.
And they dispelled it.
One of the members of the group kept telling me, you need to do this and you need to do that.
I said, what?
I'm not having anything to do with this.
I came up here to help with a certain part of it which related to what we need in this case.
Actually, I had chaired a committee that was to determine what should go into the voter conference.
Well, we did a thorough job on that aspect.
We sent to every facet of the university a questionnaire
and welcome them saying, this is what we would use it for.
These are the things that we would need.
Now, this whole project began after Mr. Rutter's death under Jack Williams?
No.
It began, let's see, I think it was under construction because didn't President Rutter die in 70?
Okay, so it was under construction.
Were we calling it the Rudder Center then?
No.
That's why.
Okay.
No, it was not.
It was just the expansion of MSC and all.
Yes.
Well, President Rudder said in Austin, that street is dividing lines.
you're responsible over here.
But don't get messing around over there.
And he said, I'm gonna tell them the same thing.
He said, the problem is that the faculty has taken over the MSC.
The kids can't meet in those rooms because of it.
And he said, I'm not gonna have it fussing back and forth.
Well, he took care of that.
He took the street out.
But that was...
That was something else.
Finally, J.O.
Adams was a great help to me.
He said,
Well, just move along.
You do this, and you watch for that, and you do this.
And I think he went to President Rutter and said, President Rutter, this fellow's got so many obligations now, you don't know which door he's coming out of.
And then they, oh, the old boy that led the choir,
Well, he was the one that was chosen.
He wouldn't take it.
I thought, oh man.
There's one way you want to blow yourself out of this place is refusing an assignment.
But he got away with it, but he did because the president lived there a lot.
But it was good in another way.
Bill Hensel took it over.
Bill is as solid as he can be.
Now were you and your group, were you all involved in any of the work that led to
the recommendations about co-education and non-compulsory core and racial integration?
Well, yes, I think so.
We, of course, everything we did was service.
Service.
I believe that that's the whole concept of guidance.
Sure.
You see, really, this first one to grab, grabbed me on what to do with it.
So he dumped it on us.
Well, that's all right.
That's what I'm hired out to do.
But we had experience there.
And so we devised this information sheet.
Now that we have this machine turned back on, Mr. Rutter dies, and you said a while ago that you were not aware of his being in poor health or anything.
Most of us, I think, were quite surprised.
Yeah.
Then General Ludeke was the interim for a few months, and then Jack Williams came.
Do you remember any first impressions of him, first acquaintances with him?
Well, yes, I remember my first meeting with him.
We had a program, and this was in 1971.
We still had our program out, the A&M adjunct.
But the legislature in its wisdom had taken it away and we wanted to acquaint the president with the program.
And we didn't know what the future was, but we wanted to do that.
Jack Dobson was the director.
I went with him because I was the administrative officer responsible, which I think was a big secret on the campus.
I think I was the only one who knew that.
The third person was the dean of liberal arts.
Because the courses, I mean, that we were offering were mostly in the liberal arts.
Now this was Maxwell?
Yes.
David Maxwell?
Yes.
He said he'd be glad to go with us.
We were walking, the three of us, from the academic building down toward the system.
And Dr. Dean Maxwell said,

Austin, I'm delighted to go down and be with President Williams and help any way I can, but he said, I don't understand why you're doing it because they are transferring everything in, I think it was the first of June.
And I said, transferring what?
And he said, you don't know?
I said, no, I don't know what you're talking about.
We are about three-fourths filled.
And you see, we'd send our material out, and he said, well, we've got a real reason to go then.
We got down there, and President Williams, as you know, he's very gracious.
He said, I understand you want to show me some things about the NMA job.
And I said, yes, Dr. Dobson is the director and he will show you.
And Jack said, I don't think I want to.
And Preston Williams said, why?
And he said, well, you're closing the thing the 1st of June and I didn't know it until about halfway down here from the academic building.
And he said, I'm not going to waste my time going over something that
Well, he meant it was handled that way.
And President Williams said, well, now wait just a minute.
He said, I've heard good reports about that program and I really would like to know what it's about.
And then he turned and buzzed Bob Cherry.
And Bob came in and he told Bob what the situation was.
And Mr. Cherry said, well, I believe the wise thing to do would be to call the board and alert them to what had happened.
And so President Williams said, well, check with each one of them and see if they would approve changing the date to September 1st.
And that's what Mr. Cherry did.
Was this the coordinating board or the A&M board?
It was the A&M board.
Oh, okay.
It was the A&M board.
And Jack was satisfied.
Jack made a good presentation.
But President Williams, though, what impressed me was that it didn't rattle him at all.
I think he kind of got a little enjoyment out of it.
He's taking a job where someone had messed up.
Now, I don't mean that critically because I understand that A&M didn't really have much say.
that this was all developed and carried out from the political side.
That's what I've always understood.
And so we really had no interest in it.
But that was another of Mr. Gilchrist's ideas.
Here was an engineer that said,

If we could have a facility where we get these young men here and we would go about in a business-like, systematic way of what college is all about, I want the best professors that we can get, and these young people will do better the first year than those who don't.
Let's see.
We'll save Williams for a little while.
Describe the adjunct.
About how long did it exist and describe the physical plant and so forth.
Well, the adjunct, as it was called, consisted of about 500 acres of land, all of which the land
Llano River flowed through.
There was a mile or so of access to the Llano River.
It had a beautiful grove of old con trees along the river bank.
It's just south of Junction.
Yes, just south of Junction.
Well, it was almost in the city limits.
It was, well now the people of Kimball County had bought this land and then turned it over to A&M.
I think that Kimball County was trying to get a two-year college and some of the more knowledgeable people in the community told me this.
A&M
felt they could make use of it, but they didn't feel strongly, apparently, about the academic two-year program, taking it on.
Well, this was in, the first year was 1951.
It was summer, 51.
And we had a contingent of freshmen that,
two six-week sessions.
And we also had the civil engineering students who did their practicum in surveying one, one six weeks from one another.
And the geologists came for their field experience.
And we were mainly a base camp for the geologists.
It was, I missed the first summer.
The rest of the time I was pretty strongly involved.
The first two or three years I taught and was the, well the equivalent of basic division.
Cliff Ransdell was the director.

Then when Dean Bertrand, for some reason, he made a move and he went from Texas A&M to the University of Las Vegas or something, somewhere up in the mountains, and became the Dean of the College of Agriculture.
Cliff then had to take over
the interim of the basic division.
That was the year then that I became the director, and I was director from 55 to 59, something like that.
Director of?
The A&M adjunct.
Of the adjunct.
That meant that I had to go out there.
Well, it was delightful, really, Haskell.
There was no ranch house on the property, and it was real nice.
It was a wood-framed house.
And out there, if you keep your windows up, you got air conditioning every night, and our children could play.
And the children of other faculty members, Dr. Segrist headed up the physical education,
And he had a very good organization.
And he had a time in the afternoon when the children of faculty could swim.
And the interesting thing was the faculty lived with the students.
That is, we lived in GI.
which GI tents and then we put permanent roofs on but we left the screens.
We ate with the students and in the in the program we had every night a professor in each of the English
would be available at the administration building to hold health sessions.
Now, by and large, what courses were offered?
Okay, English 103, at first English 100 section,
And then we had math 101 or 102.
At first it was 100.
You know that remedial stuff, after about the first two summers,
the parents and students, these sharp youngsters that looked for things, that was too good a thing.
So it didn't take but a few years, and the better students were coming out there.
And I would be filled by the first of May.
So math and English.
Math and English.
And then we moved into biology.
And we tried to teach chemistry, but it just wasn't practical.
It was a chemistry 100, but... Now, it went for how many weeks?
Six weeks.
Six weeks.
Where did those six weeks fall?
Well, they would fall from about June the 1st to middle of July.
Oh, so you could do two, there were two six weeks?
Yes.
But a student would...
